2026-04-16 12:15:25 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=["Control Output Cable (+) internal connection between cube circuitry and external lead at port 'n'"] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show 12 V correctly present on the control input (+) and 0 V on the control input (−), so the power module and its cabling to the control cube are good. With the switch closed, there should be continuity from control input (+) through the internal series path to the control output (+), yet resistance testing finds ~7.2×10¹¹ Ω (open circuit) between input (+) and output (+). The switch itself has good continuity, and the output (+) external lead is floating at 0 V. This indicates that inside the control module the circuit path from the switch/output node to the external Control Output Cable (+) at the n‑port is not connected (e.g., broken solder joint, mis‑wired, or never bonded). Therefore the fault is an internal disconnection of the control module’s output (+) conductor to its external cable at the n‑port, preventing 12 V from ever reaching the load module.'
